    "tier": "Sprint",
    "time": "~1 Week",
    "type": "Physical",
    "tagline": "Three bounces, three times in a row — no luck, pure technique.",
    "description": "Skipping stones looks like luck. It is not. It is physics — the angle of your wrist, the spin of the stone, the height of your release, the flatness of the rock you chose. Odysseus would have been a stone-skipper: patient, precise, repeating the motion until it was perfect. You will learn to read the water, choose the right stone, and throw with a sidearm flick that sends it dancing. Three bounces is your minimum. And you must do it three times in a row — because once could be a fluke. Three in a row is skill. That is what we are after.",
    "what_to_build": "Nothing — pure practice at the waterfront. Collect a personal stash of 10–15 ideal skipping stones (flat, palm-sized, smooth) to practice with.",
    "materials": [
      "access to calm water (pond, lake, or bay)",
      "collection of flat, smooth stones (self-gathered at the shore)"
    ],
    "approach": [
      "Step 1 — Learn to choose the right stone: flat, fits in your palm, smooth edges, about the size of a cookie. Collect ten good ones before you throw a single one.",
      "Step 2 — Learn the grip (index finger curled around the edge) and the sidearm release (low, parallel to the water). Practice the throwing motion on land ten times before going to the water.",
      "Step 3 — Throw your stones one at a time. Count the bounces out loud. Do not aim for distance — aim for three clean bounces. Adjust your angle and spin each throw.",
      "Step 4 — When you can get three bounces sometimes, focus on consistency. Throw ten stones and count how many hit three or more. You need to be reliable, not lucky.",
      "Step 5 — Final test: at the waterfront with a counselor watching, skip three stones in a row, each achieving three or more bounces. All three attempts must succeed consecutively."
    ],
    "kid_instructions": "\"Find the flattest, smoothest stones you can. Hold it right, throw it low, give it spin. You need three bounces — and you need to do it three times in a row. If you get two in a row and miss the third, you start over. Practice until it's not luck anymore.\"",
    "pass_criteria": "Skip a stone 3+ bounces, three consecutive times, witnessed by a counselor at the waterfront.",
    "counselor_notes": "Wind and chop make this much harder — test on a calm day or in a sheltered cove. If conditions are poor, reschedule rather than failing the kid unfairly."
